How Travel Prices developed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies sold only trips to the countries of the socialist bloc in a crushing majority, since travel to the west was very limited.
The Czech tourists thus travelled on vacation to the sea to the NDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi na Krym near the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime bowed to the West and the journeys of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the era of socialism was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel freely individually even within socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation from that country, otherwise it was not an individual trip.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand up overnight with the sleeper or to have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
However, that was not the case.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not made to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely variable currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) to travel to the West.
The Czechs, however, often spent their vacations in the country, which resulted in a large number of chats and cottages that the Czechs had acquired, and this habit is still alive today.
The journey of the Czech Republic has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 she was vacationed in NDR or Bulgaria with our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox that we are not aware of today is that it was not possible for us to travel freely to the present most popular Croatia until 1989, since it was part of Yugoslavia.
Immediately in the late 1990s, visa waivers occurred in neighbouring Western European countries, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits mainly to Austria's Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovakians couldn't get enough trips to the West for a while, everybody wanted to look at it.
In Paris, for example, Czech tours in parks in tents slept, since our incomes back then did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of the Czechs' journey was at this time driving their own food, cans, salami, etc. to be spared.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely interchangeable Czech crown, finally allowing our tourists to buy the Western currency freely after many decades.
However, our standard of living and our average wages have risen, which led to another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have been regularly preparing flights with charter airlines since 1997, making it impossible for airlines to negotiate quantitative discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had a visa-free relationship in virtually all the advanced countries of the world, except the United States, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolving travel occurred right in 2000, when due to a considerable demand it was shipped from the Czech Republic historically the first direct charter flight to exoticism, it was to Thailand.
