The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author describes it himself, quite conveniently, as "antihistoric work".
It contains several very famous names, important contracts or famous battles, on the other hand, there are almost no ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates on tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, explains the author, rather "the book about what it was like". It deals mainly with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and sorrow" combines war experiences of 20 more less fat men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives flash like the flames of candles lit in the church - new ones are added to the complex of fates while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book differs from classical historical novels.
It regulates the idea that World War I was just about the terrible trench fights on the Western Front.
Beauty and Grief also explores other places where war drama took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with bees' nests falling on them, must spend Christmas in the shade of the pyramids or face the presence of flies tse-tse.
