A lawyer who will stand before the court and try to get the law rejected will most likely be Paul Clement, who served as the U.S. Attorney General under George W. Bush's rule.
Clement's law firm, Bancroft PLLC, has been one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society group, which has been engaged in defending conservative legal principles for many years.
Another company that sponsored dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that question the law, the so-called National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc, for which huge funds are at stake in the process.
