However, the relationship between Scalia and Thomas with the two law firms active in the case, as well as companies of great financial interest in this case, was largely enough to alert ethical activists in the government.
"This shocking violation of ethics and indifference to the code of conduct is contrary to the statement by several judges that the highest court behaves according to the same rules that apply to all other federal judges," said Bob Edgar, president of the Common Cause organization.
"The judges drank and ate at the social benefit together with the legal representatives waiting to discuss their case before the court."
Their presence and assistance in obtaining funds through this action undermines their feet with any claim of impartiality, which is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas showed little understanding to their critics and told them that they also had no problem combining their judicial duties with the actions of groups such as the Federalist Society.
