The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has launched a gene research that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance is conducting research to discover the gene responsible for the obesity of children and adolescents.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to discover a gene that causes obesity in children and young people. A study called "Absence Genetics in Children and Youth" will allow you to get results on overweight.
In a report by the head of the Biochemistry Research Unit of the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Centre of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multi-disciplinary team composed of doctors, nurses, nutrition experts and social workers had been established.
This team relies on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Technical Institute (IPN).
People can come to the IMSS Sports Centres in Valle de México, where youth tests will take place every Saturday from 8 p.m.
He stressed that the research started at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexico State) and since 8 October this activity has also been carried out at the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Centre (East of the Mexican State).
As soon as data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Centre (South of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics in terms of obesity development and to identify risk factors on Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the goal is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He pointed out that every Saturday anthropometric measurements are performed with all participants (weight, height, waistline), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels are determined, and genes are examined (trying to identify genes that are involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said that this research reflects health concerns about the alarming increase in child weight.
'Health surveys carried out between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years only boys experienced an increase in obesity by 77% and girls by 47%. The dramatic increase occurred also in the event of overweight,' said an IMSS expert.
He stated that one reason for searching for indicators is that the population of the country differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This is reflected in genes responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that generally obesity genetics are usually explained as inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calories) and is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they will be given an overall assessment of the condition of children, thus determining whether they exhibit any known overweight or obesity.
He noted that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles on the neck and the forearms suggests the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and prediabetes.
The information is confidential so far, doctors hand it over in writing to their parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make to avoid their children’s disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, a day-long TV broadcast and the use of means of transport instead of walking at short distances.
Overweight also causes high calorie intake, this is a higher consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and a genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There won't be any mudslides in the UNAM asphalt
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, creates modified asphalts with polymers and thus creates a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature
If it were properly cared for, it would not be necessary to correct nearly 200,000 exodus after each rainy period in the Metropolitan Region of Valle de México, pointed out Rafael Herrera Najera, a scientist from the UNAM Chemical Faculty (FQ), who added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt landings were adequate, there would be a significant limitation of the effluents, or even it could be completely removed.
In his lecture The technological cause of the effluents that he introduced during the International Year of Chemistry announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, thereby creating a mixture of similar characteristics as asphalt, but also greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Najera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country.
He explained that asphalt, the hardest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a large molecular weight called asphalt, and others with a low molecular weight called maltens. Together, they supply asphalt with a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like fluid, at 120 degrees high viscosity, and at 50 degrees it is almost solid, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperatures, the chemical engineering expert warned.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most streets in Ciudad de México are covered with a flexible tile, which consists of six layers of materials, three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers is the asphalt cartridge, which is made of small stones poured into the asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that forms a cartridge is filled with asphalt.
When passing cars or when creating pressure, it is possible for the forces in the board to disintegrate well.
If it was a modified asphalt, it would have spread even better, a chemical engineer is suspected.
He added that on the asphalt cartridge, the last layer called the coat, made up of fine stones, is also filled with sand in the asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the vehicle’s edges, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt cartridge and must ensure the friction of the carriage.
Given that a heavy load will be placed as part of the landing, the coat must have sufficient thickness and must be kept in mind of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. In particular, water has a great impact on the function of the asphalt cartridge.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads in and it's hard to get out, it causes all the layers of the floor to soften and thus the formation of the wells.
