Nord Stream, new port of Russian gas to Europe
The far-off Nord Stream gas pipeline connecting directly to Eastern Europe to Russia and running along the Baltic Seabed has started to work.
They must supply a gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including 4 heads of state and government, took part in the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together a controlling valve controlling Russian gas entry into the Western European network.
This new pipeline starts to flow into Western Europe every year with the first pipeline of 27.5 billion additional cubic metres of Russian gas, connecting the region of St. Petersburg to the federal country of Mecklembur-Pomorana.
The second pipeline, to be completed at the end of 2012, will allow for a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, which is the amount equal to the total French consumption.
And it's already recalled the possibility of building a third pipeline pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the early completion of this huge building has the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested the project.
Nord Stream will actually allow the gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being driven over the country by any third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At once, these two countries are losing some power: the possibility of pushing Russia with threats to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed it most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", with a reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means saying it's a politically sensitive topic.
Western Europe has gained greater confidence in its purchases by supporting this Russian project.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project created gaps between Europeans from the east and the west.
Russia was barely able to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western states with high gas consumption, whose bearings are nearing their end five years ago.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us," François Fillon confirmed at the opening ceremony of this pipeline and demonstrated the point at which the major gas contracts of things are both political and economic.
All of this explains the wide smiles of the leaders of Gazprom present in a large number in Lubmin, the gas induction point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical activity.
Submarine pipes are made of steel equipped with a concrete cloak to protect them from anchors of seagoing vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea in an average depth of 200 m.
When it was built, it was necessary to avoid minefields from World War II.
"For their safety, almost a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
Measures to protect fauna and flora were also needed.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing 242 Eiffels, which is nowhere to be interrupted by valves or maintenance stations throughout its length.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project manager rejected it when the Swedes were only a little eager to see the Russian state company established on their coasts.
"In the event of a malfunction, we will stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute," Jens Müller points out.
In the event of a lack of closeness, the gas contained in the gas pipeline will escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, because the welds were designed to create a lack of intimacy once every 100,000 years.
The external gas pipeline shall be checked by a submarine robot towed by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline shall be controlled by a device that circulates within.
This unit of cigar shape with a diameter of 1 metre is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pressed by gas.
The target shall provide accurate information on possible deformations of metal parts throughout the three days of travel at a speed of 3 m/s.
The long-distance pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without any minor repairs needed.
The gas circulation is simply secured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar on start and 100 bar on target.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds a 51% share.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as by the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint company called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company has a seat in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased this company for five years with a contract that could be renewed all its gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will benefit from total capacity, any amount of real gas transported," Jens Müller points out.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was provided by 30% shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipes.
For the GDF group, Suez's investment costs went up to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be returned to them, because only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline comes from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine trees.
The vents are an output gate of about five feet [4.5 m] high.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before being transported to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received 1 million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
When full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
