Why is there such a high proportion of unemployed disabled workers?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
Today, the 15th week of disabled employment opens.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed people with disabilities is even twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the whole population.
Is it exclamating?
"No, he's underlining Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt Association, who organizes the Week for the Employment of the Disabled."
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable."
"At that time, there was not a percentage of the unemployed twice, but three times higher."
"There's nothing left to do."
It must be said that there are many obstacles to unemployed people before they enter the workplace.
These are elderly: 37% is over 50 (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% have no degree and out of 2.3 million high school students there are only 10,000 disabled.
Finally - long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% in disabled people compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that particularly complicate the return to employment and which represent the "core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin Association, which was established in 1992 to help businesses receive disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
Unspoken, there are ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
Studies conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cite Association found that the surveyed managers have a "weak level of knowledge of disabled persons" with an "excessive idea of people in driving chairs and mental or mental disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the goal of employing 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The last known numbers from 2008 give a status equal to 2.6%.
"Now we are moving about 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph's organisation entrusted with collecting fees from businesses that do not comply with this law.
The evidence is the number of "punished" enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 more guilty companies to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large businesses."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
